%S A394717 55,91,175,275,325,385,505,715,1045,1375,1729,1825,2275,2525,3425,
%T A394717 4375,5005,6175,6533,6875,8125,8149,9625,10001,10625,12625,14645,
%U A394717 17875,19201,21931,34375,41125,45625,50851,56875,63125,71875,73645,83125,85625,90805,94139,95095
%N A394717 Composite numbers d such that the period k of the decimal expansion of 1/d is even and divides d-1, and the two halves of the repetend of 1/d sum to 10^(k/2) - 1.
%C A394717 Composite numbers passing two independent tests that all primes p (other than 2 and 5) with even period pass: the period of 1/p divides p-1, and the halves of the repetend of 1/p sum to a string of 9's (Midy's theorem, 1836). The first condition makes this a subsequence of A351396.
%C A394717 Equivalently: d is a term iff d is in A351396 with even period k and 10^(k/2) == -1 (mod d'), where d' is d with all factors of 2 and 5 removed.
%C A394717 The terms coprime to 10 are exactly the strong pseudoprimes to base 10 (A020236) whose Miller-Rabin sequence reaches -1; verified for all d <= 1276666539. Midy's nines-complement property asserts that -1 lies among the powers of 10 modulo d', which is the -1 witness of the base-10 Miller-Rabin test.
%C A394717 All terms are odd (an even k dividing d-1 forces d odd). No term is divisible by 3 (10 == 1 mod 3, so no power of 10 is -1 mod 3). Terms divisible by 5 occur (55 is the first), so this sequence is not contained in any base-10 Fermat or strong pseudoprime sequence.
%C A394717 Of the 43 Carmichael numbers in A351396 below 10^6, only 1729 is a term.
%C A394717 If p^2 divides a term for a prime p other than 5, then p is a Wieferich prime to base 10 (A045616): for non-Wieferich p, the multiplicative order of 10 modulo p^2 is p times the order modulo p, so p would divide the period k, contradicting k | d-1. The first nonsquarefree term is 237169 = 487^2.
%C A394717 Since no term is divisible by 3, the only prime whose square can divide a term below 56598313^2 = 3203369034445969 is 487. 56598313^2 is itself a term: 10 is a primitive root modulo the Wieferich prime 56598313, so 1/56598313^2 has the even period 56598312, which divides 56598313^2 - 1, and 10 raised to half the period is -1 in the cyclic group modulo 56598313^2.
%H A394717 Barry Smyth, <a href="/A394717/b394717.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1107</a>
%H A394717 J. Lewittes, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0605182">Midy's Theorem for Periodic Decimals</a>, arXiv:math/0605182 [math.NT], 2006.
%H A394717 Étienne Midy, <a href="https://archive.org/details/1014596483">De quelques propriétés des nombres et des fractions décimales périodiques</a>, 1836.
%H A394717 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midy%27s_theorem">Midy's theorem</a>.
%e A394717 91 = 7*13 is a term: 1/91 = 0.010989010989..., the period 6 divides 90, and 010 + 989 = 999.
%e A394717 55 = 5*11 is a term: 1/55 = 0.0181818..., the period 2 divides 54, and 1 + 8 = 9.
%e A394717 259 = 7*37 is not a term: it is in A351396 (period 6 divides 258) but 1/259 = 0.003861003861... and 003 + 861 = 864, not 999.
%o A394717 (Python)
%o A394717 from sympy import isprime, n_order
%o A394717 def ok(d):
%o A394717     if d < 4 or isprime(d):
%o A394717         return False
%o A394717     dr = d
%o A394717     while dr % 2 == 0: dr //= 2
%o A394717     while dr % 5 == 0: dr //= 5
%o A394717     if dr == 1:
%o A394717         return False
%o A394717     k = n_order(10, dr)
%o A394717     return k % 2 == 0 and (d-1) % k == 0 and pow(10, k//2, dr) == dr-1
%o A394717 print([d for d in range(2, 25000) if ok(d)])
%Y A394717 Subsequence of A351396. Cf. A020236 (the coprime-to-10 terms are its -1 branch), A005939, A350598 (a different subsequence of A351396, selecting first occurrences of each repetend), A045616 (the only primes whose squares can divide terms), A187040 (all numbers with Midy's property: this sequence consists of the composite terms of A187040 whose period divides d-1).
